'''Zedekiah Johnson Purnell''' (born 1813) was an African-American activist, businessman, and editor of the literary journal [[The Demosthenian Shield]].<ref name="Winch, Julie">{{cite book|last=Winch|first=Julie|title=The Elite of Our People: Joseph Willsonâ€™s Sketches of Black Upper-Class Life in Antebellum Philadelphia|date=2000|publisher=Pennsylvania State University Press|location=State College|isbn=9780271043029|page=159|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W6VNGI_i17UC&dq=demosthenian+shield&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> In the 1840s, Purnell emerged on the national stage as an outspoken proponent of an African-American press, supporting such authors as [[Charles Bennett Ray]] and [[Samuel Cornish]].<ref name="Winch, Julie" />

==Early life==

Zedekiah Johnson Purnell was born in Philadelphia in 1813, in one of the most socially active families in Philadelphia's black community.  <!--Insert a description here of the person's birth and early life.-->

==Career==

He began work as a sailor, but eventually changed careers for "a more stable life ashore", becoming a hairdresser and a successful businessowner, located on the corner of Carpenter & Decatur Streets.  As of the 1860 Philadelphia Census, his real estate property was valued at approximately $1100.  His personal estate was valued at $400.
<!--A description of the major works of the person's life, with sub-sections for different focuses. You can change the name of this section to reflect the main focus of the person's adult life.-->

==Activism==

Purnell began his work as a "champion of the black press" in 1839 when he helped to found an organization that would become known as the Demosthenian Institute, "a literary society of colored young men".  He was an avid supporter of [[Samuel Cornish]] and [[Charles B. Ray]]'s ''[[The Colored American (New York City)|Colored American]]'' and [[Martin R. Delany]]'s ''Mystery''. <!--A description of the person's activities as an activist.-->
